## 6. Add useful fallback tracing

Add this near the JIT globals:

```cpp
static uint32_t g_dbgFallback = 0;
static uint32_t g_dbgNormal   = 0;
```

Then update `runCpu()`:

```cpp
if (reason == EXIT_FALLBACK) {
    if (g_dbgFallback++ < 128) {
        printf("[JIT] fallback cpu=%d mode=%s pc=%08X next=%08X cpsr=%08X\n",
               cpu,
               gba ? "gba" : "nds",
               pc,
               expc,
               interp.getCpsrRef());
    }

    if (validPC(expc, gba))
        interp.setPC(expc);

    interp.jitRunOpcode();
    return;
}

if (g_dbgNormal++ < 32) {
    printf("[JIT] normal cpu=%d mode=%s pc=%08X -> %08X\n",
           cpu,
           gba ? "gba" : "nds",
           pc,
           expc);
}
```

This will immediately tell you whether:

1. The JIT is compiling Thumb blocks.
2. It is falling back because of unsupported instructions.
3. PC becomes corrupt before or after the JIT block.
4. GBA execution reaches ROM at `0x08000000`.

